Anonymous Thu 22 Mar 2018 20:02:55 No.14707142 Report
Quoted By:
>>14698040
The problem with Janeway was that they presented her as a tough character making tough, questionable decisions, but never went very deep into questioning those decisions in the writing. Picard and Sisko periodically lose control over the situations they're in, their decisions are clouded by their experiences and their personal judgement. The most iconic episode of Sisko's comparitively grey morality is essentially him being bamboozled by Garak into doing something that he wouldn't do on his own, but could live with when Garak forces his hand.

That knife edge of morality is lacking in Voyager, and Janeway is not consistent in her convictions. She'll break the Prime Directive in one episode, but preach about it in the next, with no acknowledgement of the contrast. TNG also has episodes, especially in seasons 1 and 2, that are written in the same way, and they're generally regarded as poor episodes.

They put Janeway on a pedestal too much, while also writing her very inconsistently.

>It’s was late on a Sunday night
